sub_title: PHD Candidate at Technische Universiteit Delft
summary:
I am a PhD candidate in 3D city models for energy applications  in the 3D geoinformation research group, which is part of the Department of Urbanism of the Faculty of Architecture & the Built Environment at the Delft University of Technology in the Netherlands.

I hold a MSc in Geodesy and Geoinformation Science from the Technische Uniersität Berlin in Germany as well as a MSc in Computer Science and Communications and a BSC in Cadaster Engineering and Geodesy from the District University in Colombia

projects: [{'title': 'Estimation of Electric Energy Demand using 3D City Models', 'date': {'start': {'month': 11, 'day': None, 'year': 2012}, 'end': {'month': 6, 'day': None, 'year': 2013}}, 'description': 'In this research, a methodology for the estimation of electrical energy demand of buildings using a 3D city model (CityGML) was done. The idea of including that kind of data lies in the fact that nowadays those models are rich of geometric and semantical data, which could be useful in energy demand forecasting. \n\nSome comprehensive tools for processing CityGML files were used (Cityjml4j, FME, ArcGIS, Java Topology Suite) were considered during the implementation phase, the area of study was located in the borough of Charlottenburg in Berlin. The results of the area of study were evaluated with official statistical data of Berlin.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Camilo', 'last_name': 'Leon-Sanchez', 'name': None, 'headline': 'PHD Candidate at Technische Universiteit Delft'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Thomas', 'last_name': 'Adolphi', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Projektmanager bei virtualcitySYSTEMS'}]}, {'title': 'GIS Project - Indoor Navigation', 'date': {'start': {'month': 10, 'day': None, 'year': 2011}, 'end': {'month': 3, 'day': None, 'year': 2012}}, 'description': 'The task of the GIS Project, in the frames of the study program, was to implement an indoor navigation system for two specified areas of the university. The team was divided in four groups. Each group was assigned  different tasks, such as acquirement of WLAN measurements, 3D modelling of the building, creation of interpolation maps, finding the shortest route using geodatabases etc. In the end of the period, the results from the groups where combined.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Camilo', 'last_name': 'Leon-Sanchez', 'name': None, 'headline': 'PHD Candidate at Technische Universiteit Delft'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Dimitris', 'last_name': 'Karakostis', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Geospatial Team Leader at World Food Programme'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Vasileia', 'last_name': 'Apostolidou', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Manager Business Analyst at Pfizer Center for Digital Innovation'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Sowmiya Narayanan', 'last_name': 'K J', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Geospatial Researcher | Experienced Software Professional | Founder'}]}]
